-- Enrichment marathon batch: Fathom Analytics, Faved, Feast, FeatBit, Feathery, Featurebase, Fedora Repository, FeedHive

-- ── Fathom Analytics ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Fathom Analytics is a privacy-first, cookieless website analytics platform that gives businesses simple, GDPR-compliant traffic insights without tracking personal data or requiring a cookie consent banner.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (usage-based, priced by monthly pageviews), plus a free open-source self-hosted edition$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$15/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1-10 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Victoria, British Columbia, Canada$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Fathom Analytics Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Fathom Analytics review covering features, pricing tiers, privacy compliance, and how this cookieless Google Analytics alternative compares to Plausible and Simple Analytics.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Fathom Analytics is a privacy-focused, cookieless website analytics platform built as a simpler, compliance-friendly alternative to Google Analytics. It tracks website traffic, page views, referrers, UTM campaign performance, custom events, and e-commerce conversions without placing cookies on visitor devices and without collecting personally identifiable information, which the company positions as making it compliant with GDPR, CCPA, PECR, and ePrivacy regulations without requiring a cookie consent banner on the sites that use it. The product is delivered as a single lightweight JavaScript snippet, described by the company as roughly 2 kilobytes, that site owners add to their pages, after which visits are recorded anonymously and surfaced in a real-time dashboard. Fathom markets itself around three ideas: simplicity of the dashboard compared to the complexity of Google Analytics, respect for visitor privacy through anonymized, cookieless data collection, and faster page-load performance from a minimal tracking script.

The company originated from a tweet. In 2018, writer and designer Paul Jarvis posted a mockup of what he thought a simpler, privacy-respecting analytics dashboard could look like, frustrated that mainstream analytics tools like Google Analytics had become bloated and complex. The idea attracted enough interest that Jarvis pursued it, first releasing an open-source, self-hosted version of the product known as Fathom Lite. Developer Jack Ellis joined as a technical co-founder in early 2019, and the paid, cloud-hosted version of Fathom Analytics began to grow from there, funded entirely by customer revenue rather than venture capital. The company describes itself as fully bootstrapped and '100% independently owned,' explicitly rejecting outside investment so it can prioritize sustainability and customer trust over rapid, VC-driven growth. Jarvis has since stepped back from day-to-day operations, with Ellis now running the company; Fathom also employs a dedicated Privacy Officer, reflecting how central compliance positioning is to the product's identity. The company is small and remote-first, publicly describing itself as a full-time team of only a handful of people distributed across different countries, based out of Victoria, British Columbia, Canada.

Technically, Fathom Analytics runs on a serverless cloud architecture rather than traditional fixed servers. According to the company's own infrastructure documentation, incoming pageview and event data is received by an AWS Lambda layer that scales automatically with traffic, then queued through Amazon SQS using FIFO (first-in-first-out) ordering across multiple availability zones to preserve reliability during traffic spikes. Background worker clusters then process this queued data into SingleStore, a distributed, horizontally scalable SQL database designed for high-throughput analytical workloads, which Fathom says is also used by large enterprises such as Intel, Sony, Dell, and Uber for similarly demanding data volumes. This pipeline is what allows Fathom to promise near real-time dashboard updates even for high-traffic websites, along with what the company calls 'forever data retention,' meaning historical analytics data remains fully accessible for as long as a customer's account is active, rather than being sampled, aggregated, or purged after a fixed retention window as some competing tools do.

Fathom's pricing is structured entirely around monthly pageview volume rather than feature tiers, meaning every paying customer, regardless of plan size, gets the same feature set: event tracking, e-commerce tracking, UTM campaign tracking, saved and shareable dashboards, automatic bot and spam filtering, full API access, and unlimited email reports and CSV exports. Customers choose a plan based on their expected average monthly pageviews, starting around $15 per month for up to roughly 100,000 monthly pageviews, with published tiers scaling upward through roughly 200,000, 500,000, 1 million, 2 million, 5 million, 10 million, and 15 million pageviews, each carrying a progressively higher flat monthly fee; sites with especially high traffic (above roughly 15 to 25 million monthly pageviews) are directed to contact Fathom directly for custom enterprise pricing. Every plan includes a base allotment of sites (fifty on the entry plan), with additional sites purchasable in packs. All plans include a seven-day free trial before billing begins, and customers who pay annually receive the equivalent of about two months free compared to paying monthly. Fathom states plainly that it does not run discounts or seasonal sales, keeping pricing consistent year-round, and that customers can cancel at any time and export all of their data. Separately, the company also maintains Fathom Lite, a free, open-source, self-hosted version of the original analytics concept, distributed on GitHub and downloaded millions of times, intended for developers and hobbyists who want a no-cost, privacy-respecting analytics tool they can run and maintain on their own infrastructure without official support.

The target audience for the hosted Fathom Analytics product spans indie developers, small and mid-sized businesses, agencies managing analytics across many client websites, and larger organizations with legal or compliance teams that specifically require analytics tooling that avoids cookie banners and personal-data collection. The company highlights that it has been used by well over a million websites and lists customers and users that include GitHub, IBM, HashiCorp, Bootstrap, Laravel, and reportedly some government and Fortune 100 organizations, alongside prominent independent creators and small businesses that value the product's simplicity and privacy stance. Because Fathom charges a single flat rate per pageview tier regardless of how many sites are attached (within the included site allowance), it is frequently recommended for agencies and freelancers who run analytics across a portfolio of client sites, since the per-site marginal cost is very low compared to per-site pricing models used by some competitors.

Within the privacy-analytics category, Fathom's most frequently cited competitors are Plausible Analytics, Simple Analytics, Matomo, and, more distantly, Google Analytics itself as the incumbent it explicitly positions against. Plausible is typically described as the more open option, being fully open source with a self-hostable core and a comparable cookieless, lightweight-script approach, and independent comparisons generally note that Plausible offers a broader set of built-in analytics capabilities (such as funnels and goal conversion breakdowns) at a similar or lower price point. Simple Analytics is generally positioned as an even more minimal, beginner-friendly tool aimed at non-technical users who want the absolute simplest possible dashboard. Fathom differentiates itself less on raw feature depth and more on its compliance-first reputation: the company publishes detailed documentation of its legal and privacy approach, says it has engaged outside privacy-law experts to review its practices, and is frequently cited by reviewers as the tool that legal, compliance, and procurement teams feel most comfortable approving, particularly for regulated or enterprise-adjacent environments.

Several additional facts round out Fathom's public profile. The company reports having processed billions of pageviews across its history and serving thousands of paying customers on top of the free Fathom Lite user base. It states it has never sold customer or visitor data and does not rely on advertising-driven business models, framing its subscription-only revenue as core to its privacy claims being credible rather than just a marketing position. The product integrates with a wide range of platforms and frameworks, including WordPress, Webflow, Next.js, Vue.js, and email/marketing tools like ConvertKit, generally through a single script tag or a small plugin, making it accessible to non-developers as well as engineering teams. From an architectural standpoint, the choice of a serverless, queue-based ingestion pipeline backed by a distributed SQL database is notable for an analytics company of Fathom's relatively small headcount, reflecting a deliberate strategy of using managed cloud infrastructure to achieve enterprise-grade reliability and scale without needing a large operations team.

In terms of market position and evolution, Fathom has remained a bootstrapped, privately owned company throughout its history, resisting acquisition or outside funding in a market segment where several competitors have taken venture investment or been acquired by larger analytics or hosting companies. Its pricing structure has evolved over time, most notably a publicized 2019 update in which the company added intermediate pageview tiers between its original 100,000 and 1,000,000 pageview plans, explicitly to better serve 'regular-sized businesses' rather than chase large enterprise contracts that might have required compromising its privacy-first product principles. This history of deliberately turning down growth opportunities that conflict with its stated values, combined with its emphasis on transparency around infrastructure and compliance, has become a core part of how Fathom differentiates itself in a crowded field of privacy-oriented analytics alternatives to Google Analytics.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '9974bf44-ff46-4392-bd8f-98b3ee10f69b';

