-- ── Faved ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Faved is an open-source, privacy-first bookmark manager that lets users organize large link collections with customizable nested tags, available as a free self-hosted app or a paid managed cloud service.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted, open source); Cloud plan from $2.50/month billed annually$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2025, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Faved Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Faved is an open-source bookmark manager with nested tags and self-hosting. See features, pricing tiers, pros and cons, and top alternatives like Raindrop.io.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Faved is an open-source, privacy-first bookmark manager built to help individuals and teams save, tag, and retrieve large collections of web links without losing control of their data. Marketed under the tagline 'Organize Your Bookmarks,' the product is positioned as an alternative to flat, folder-based bookmarking tools and to closed, cloud-only services. Its central design idea is a nested, customizable tagging system: instead of forcing links into a single rigid folder tree, users can apply colored, hierarchical tags that can be pinned for quick access, letting a single bookmark live in multiple overlapping categories. The project explicitly targets people who have outgrown simple browser bookmarks or who have hit the organizational and performance limits of mainstream services, while also appealing to privacy-conscious users who want the option to run the software entirely on their own infrastructure.

Faved was created by Denis Dvali, a developer who previously worked at Automattic and who also founded the uptime-monitoring service Uptimely.cloud. According to Faved's own blog post introducing the project, Dvali built it out of frustration with third-party bookmarking apps that 'vanish or lock away your data' and with bloated tools that added complexity without solving the core problem of quickly saving and finding links. The Faved codebase was published to GitHub under the account 'denho' on June 26, 2025, and the product was subsequently listed on BetaList with a public launch date of July 23, 2025, where early adopters were offered a limited-time discount code for the first year of the paid Cloud plan. Because the project is only months old as of this writing, it does not have the extended corporate history, funding rounds, or acquisition milestones typical of larger SaaS companies; it reads instead as an indie, founder-led open-source project that has quickly attracted community attention, accumulating roughly 1,100 to 1,200 GitHub stars and around 65 forks in its first year.

Technically, Faved is built with a TypeScript and React frontend styled using Tailwind CSS and the Shadcn UI component library, bundled with Vite. The backend runs on PHP 8 with a SQLite database, served via Apache, and the entire stack is packaged for Docker so that self-hosters can deploy it with a single command and no external dependencies. This lightweight, dependency-minimal architecture is a deliberate choice: the project is described as loading even large bookmark libraries in well under 100 milliseconds, and the self-hosted deployment model means that all bookmark data, tags, and metadata are stored locally on infrastructure the user controls rather than on a third-party server, unless the user opts into the managed Cloud offering.

Core product features include automatic metadata fetching, where Faved retrieves a page's title, description, and preview image at the moment a link is saved, along with built-in duplicate detection to keep large libraries clean. The interface supports instant, flexible search and sorting, bulk actions for managing many bookmarks at once, and a fully responsive layout across mobile, tablet, and desktop that can be installed as a Progressive Web App for a native-app-like experience, complete with light and dark mode that syncs with system settings. Users can capture new bookmarks in several ways: a Chrome browser extension, a lightweight bookmarklet that works in any browser without requiring an extension install, and native Share menu integration on iPhone, iPad, and Mac, with additional support for Apple Shortcuts automation. For people switching from other tools, Faved provides import functionality that pulls bookmarks from Chrome, Safari, Firefox, and Edge while preserving original folder structures by converting them into nested tags, and it offers dedicated migration paths from Raindrop.io and Pocket that retain existing collections and tags.

Faved's pricing is structured around three tiers. The Self-Hosted tier is free and open source under the MIT license, supports unlimited bookmarks, and gives users complete ownership of their data since everything runs on infrastructure they control; this tier is the direct product of the GitHub repository and requires the user to run their own Docker deployment. The Cloud tier is a managed, hosted version of the same product priced at $2.50 per month when billed annually (billed as $30 per year), and it includes a 14-day free trial. Cloud accounts support up to 50,000 bookmarks and add conveniences that self-hosting does not automatically provide, such as encryption, automatic backups, automatic software updates, early access to new features, and email support. The top tier, Cloud Team, is aimed at organizations and is priced on a custom, contact-for-pricing basis; it removes the bookmark cap entirely, adds multi-user access and user management, single sign-on (SSO), custom branding, and priority support, positioning it as the option for teams that want the convenience of a hosted service with shared, collaborative libraries.

The target audience for Faved splits into a few overlapping groups. Self-hosting enthusiasts and developers who prioritize data ownership and are comfortable running a Docker container make up the core early-adopter base, drawn by the MIT license and the promise of a codebase they can inspect, audit, and extend themselves. Knowledge workers, researchers, and heavy internet users who have accumulated large, unwieldy bookmark collections and need a faster, more structured way to tag and retrieve links are a second core segment, served primarily by the paid Cloud tier's convenience and higher capacity. A third segment is small teams and organizations that want a shared, collaboratively maintained link library with access controls and SSO, which the Cloud Team plan is built to serve.

In the bookmark-management category, Faved competes most directly with Raindrop.io, a long-established freemium bookmarking service; wallabag, an open-source read-it-later and archiving tool; and Karakeep (formerly known as Hoarder), another self-hostable bookmark and content collection manager. It is also frequently discussed alongside Pocket, the Mozilla-owned read-it-later app that Faved explicitly supports migrating away from. Faved differentiates itself from these competitors primarily through its combination of a fully open-source, self-hostable core with a genuinely optional paid cloud layer, its emphasis on nested and color-customizable tags rather than flat folders or simple labels, its stated sub-100-millisecond load performance even on large libraries, and its lightweight PHP and SQLite backend, which keeps the self-hosted footprint small compared to heavier alternatives built on larger database engines or more complex service architectures.

As a young, founder-led project, Faved's public roadmap and blog signal continued iteration rather than a settled, mature product. Stated future plans include full-page archiving (capturing a snapshot of a page's content rather than just a link), enhanced search capabilities, offline access on mobile, and an expanded managed-hosting offering intended to make the tool more accessible to non-technical users who do not want to run Docker themselves. The project maintains a public Discord community and an X/Twitter presence for support and updates, which is typical of early-stage open-source products building a user base through direct community engagement rather than enterprise sales or large marketing budgets. Overall, Faved represents a modern entrant in the bookmark-management space that leans heavily on open-source credibility, data-ownership messaging, and a fast, tag-centric interface to differentiate itself from both legacy bookmarking tools and larger commercial read-it-later platforms.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '3185965d-fd1d-45c7-a0e1-03ac82f24008';

