-- ── Feast ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Feast is an open source feature store that lets machine learning and AI teams define, store, and serve features consistently for both model training and real-time inference.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Feast Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Feast is a free, open source feature store for ML and RAG. See how it works, its architecture, pricing, pros and cons, and top alternatives like Tecton.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Feast, short for 'feature store,' is an open source feature store built for machine learning teams that need to define, manage, and serve features consistently across model training and real-time production inference. At its core, Feast solves a specific engineering problem: the same underlying data attributes (a user's rolling purchase count, a merchant's fraud score, a driver's average trip rating) need to be computed once, stored centrally, and then made available in two very different contexts, as large historical batches for training models and as low-latency lookups for scoring live requests, without the values drifting apart between the two paths. Feast provides the abstractions, storage integrations, and APIs needed to do this without every team reinventing the same pipeline.

The project began in 2018 as a collaboration between Gojek, the Indonesia-based ride-hailing and on-demand services company (then styled GO-JEK), and Google Cloud. Gojek had more than ten internal machine learning teams building production systems for pricing, matchmaking, fraud detection, and recommendations, and each team was independently building and operating its own feature infrastructure, leading to duplicated engineering effort and inconsistent feature definitions. Gojek partnered with Google Cloud's engineering teams to design a shared solution, and the two companies jointly open sourced Feast, publicly announced via a Google Cloud blog post on January 19, 2019, with Gojek's Peter Richens quoted describing Feast as an essential component of the company's end-to-end ML systems. The original design paired a BigQuery-based offline store for historical retrieval with a Redis-based online store for low-latency serving, reflecting the Google Cloud and Gojek stacks of the time.

In 2020, governance of Feast moved to the Linux Foundation for AI, which later became the LF AI and Data Foundation, giving the project neutral, vendor-independent stewardship rather than being controlled by a single company. That same year, the venture-backed startup Tecton, founded by engineers who had previously built Uber's Michelangelo feature platform, became a core contributor to Feast, investing significant engineering resources into rearchitecting the project and helping define the feature store category more broadly, while also building its own commercial, managed feature platform on a separate codebase. Over the following years the maintainer and contributor base broadened well beyond its original founders to include engineers from Affirm, Red Hat, J.P. Morgan, AWS, Azure, Snowflake, Redis, DataStax, Bytewax, and other companies, along with independent open source contributors, reflecting Feast's evolution into a genuinely community-governed project rather than a single-vendor effort.

Technically, Feast is organized around a small number of composable building blocks rather than a single monolithic service. An offline store handles historical feature extraction for model training and batch scoring, and can be backed by data warehouses and query engines such as BigQuery, Snowflake, Redshift, Postgres, Spark, Trino, DuckDB, Athena, ClickHouse, or Azure Synapse. An online store serves precomputed feature values with low latency for real-time inference, with supported backends including Redis, DynamoDB, Google Bigtable and Datastore, Cassandra and AstraDB, ScyllaDB, MySQL, Postgres, SQLite, Hazelcast, Elasticsearch, and Aerospike, among others. Because Feast treats these stores as pluggable connectors rather than baked-in dependencies, teams can adopt it on top of infrastructure they already operate rather than migrating to a new database.

Sitting above the two stores is the registry, a central metadata catalog that records feature definitions, entities, data sources, and feature views, giving teams a shared, discoverable source of truth for what features exist and how they are computed, similar in spirit to a schema registry for feature engineering. A Python SDK and command-line interface let engineers declare entities, data sources, and feature views as code, apply those definitions to the registry, and materialize (push) computed values from the offline store into the online store on a schedule or via streaming ingestion. An optional feature server exposes a REST or gRPC-style API so that non-Python applications and services can read and write features without embedding the Python SDK directly, which is important for organizations serving predictions from Java, Go, or other application runtimes.

Feast's most distinctive technical contribution is point-in-time correct feature retrieval, sometimes called time-travel joins. When assembling a training dataset, Feast joins historical feature values to labeled training examples using the exact timestamp of each event, ensuring that a model only ever trains on the feature values that would genuinely have been available at prediction time. This prevents a common and hard-to-detect class of bug called label leakage or time travel leakage, where a model trains on future information it would never see in production, giving inflated offline metrics that collapse once the model is deployed. Feast automates this join logic across supported offline stores so that individual teams do not need to hand-write it themselves for every project.

More recently, Feast has expanded beyond strictly tabular, structured features into supporting vector embeddings and similarity search, positioning the project for retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) and other large language model workloads in addition to traditional ML. Newer releases add integrations with vector-capable stores such as Qdrant, Milvus, Faiss, Elasticsearch, and Couchbase, allowing teams to store and retrieve embeddings alongside conventional numeric and categorical features through the same registry and serving layer, plus data quality monitoring and observability tooling such as baseline metrics, audit logging, and REST APIs for inspecting served features. This reflects a broader shift in the project's positioning from a pure 'ML feature store' toward a more general 'data platform for AI applications,' spanning classic supervised learning, recommendation and fraud models, and newer generative AI and RAG use cases.

Because Feast is released under the permissive Apache License 2.0, it is free to download, self-host, inspect, modify, and redistribute, and there is no paid tier, subscription, or usage-based fee charged by the Feast project itself; the software is entirely open source. Organizations that adopt Feast are responsible for hosting and operating the underlying offline and online store infrastructure themselves, whether on their own servers or on managed cloud database and warehouse services from providers like AWS, Google Cloud, Snowflake, or Redis, so the real-world cost of running Feast is the infrastructure and engineering time required to operate it, not a license fee. There is no first-party managed Feast-as-a-service offering from the Feast project itself, though the commercial vendor Tecton offers a separate managed feature platform aimed at teams who want similar capabilities without operating the open source stack directly.

Feast's target audience is data and machine learning engineering teams at organizations with real production ML systems, typically mid-to-large technology companies, fintechs, and enterprises that already operate data warehouses and low-latency key-value stores and want to standardize feature management across multiple model teams rather than build one-off pipelines per model. Named public adopters and contributors cited by the project include Robinhood, NVIDIA, Discord, Walmart, Shopify, Salesforce, Adyen, IBM, and SeatGeek, and the project reports figures such as roughly 7,000-plus GitHub stars, around 12 million-plus package downloads, several thousand Slack community members, and contributions from close to 300 individuals, indicating a mature and actively maintained open source ecosystem.

Within the feature store category, Feast is most often compared to Tecton, Hopsworks, AWS SageMaker Feature Store, and Databricks Feature Store (formerly part of Databricks' MLOps suite), as well as newer entrants like Fennel. Feast's differentiation is its vendor-neutral, bring-your-own-infrastructure model under Linux Foundation governance: it is free and highly configurable, connecting to whichever offline and online stores an organization already runs, but it requires teams to assemble and operate that infrastructure themselves. Tecton, by contrast, is a fully managed commercial platform with built-in streaming feature computation, freshness monitoring, and data quality alerting, generally offering lower operational burden at the cost of usage-based pricing. Hopsworks sits between the two, offering both self-hosted and managed deployment options with more built-in tooling than Feast but at lower cost than Tecton, and has gained particular traction in regulated industries like finance and healthcare. AWS SageMaker Feature Store and Databricks Feature Store are cloud-native options that integrate tightly with their respective platforms' training and deployment pipelines but offer less portability outside those ecosystems.

In terms of product evolution, the Feast maintainer community has described the project's current trajectory publicly as 'the road to 1.0,' signaling an effort to stabilize APIs, consolidate the growing list of offline and online store integrations, and formalize governance under its post-Gojek, post-single-vendor maintainer base, which now spans contributors from Affirm, Red Hat, J.P. Morgan, and independent engineers alongside continuing involvement from Tecton and the broader cloud and database ecosystem. Combined with its expansion into vector search and RAG support, this positions Feast as an actively evolving, community-governed infrastructure layer for both classic machine learning and modern generative AI applications, rather than a static or abandoned early-2019 project.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f7aac8e5-93a6-4551-b76b-53dae46d786f';

