-- ── FeatBit ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FeatBit is an open-source, self-hostable feature flag and experimentation platform built with .NET that lets engineering teams decouple code deployment from feature release, target users, run A/B tests, and roll back instantly without redeploying.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted, MIT-licensed Foundation tier)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2022, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FeatBit Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FeatBit review: open-source, self-hosted feature flag platform with A/B testing, targeting, and AI-native release tools. See pricing, features, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FeatBit is an open-source feature flag management and experimentation platform that gives engineering and product teams a way to control software releases independently of code deployments. At its core, FeatBit lets developers wrap new functionality in a feature flag, then decide at runtime which users, segments, or percentage of traffic see that functionality, all without shipping a new build. This decouples the act of deploying code from the act of releasing a feature to end users, which is the central value proposition shared by every product in the feature-management category, including market leader LaunchDarkly. FeatBit differentiates itself primarily through its open-source, self-hostable architecture: the bulk of its codebase is released under the permissive MIT license, and the company positions the product as a low-cost, infrastructure-owned alternative to proprietary SaaS feature flag vendors that typically charge per seat, per environment, or per monthly active user (MAU).

The project lives in the public GitHub repository featbit/featbit, which was created in August 2022 and has accumulated roughly 1.9 thousand stars and around 140 forks as of mid-2026, indicating a moderately active open-source community relative to niche developer-infrastructure tools. The repository description reads 'Enterprise-grade feature flag platform that you can self-host. Get started - free,' which captures the project's self-hosting-first philosophy. The commercial entity behind the project is FeatBit Inc., which also operates affiliated entities for contracting purposes; the company maintains an active presence on GitHub, Discord, LinkedIn, YouTube, and X (formerly Twitter), and can be reached at contact@featbit.co. Precise public details about FeatBit's founding story, headquarters city, and current headcount are not consistently documented across first-party and third-party sources, so those specific facts are treated as unverified rather than stated definitively.

Technically, FeatBit is built primarily in C# on .NET, with a web management console written in Angular (TypeScript, HTML, and Less), and it uses MongoDB as its primary data store, with documented support for alternatives such as Azure Cosmos DB and PostgreSQL via FerretDB for teams that prefer a relational-compatible backend. Redis is used for caching and message queuing between services. The platform's defining technical feature is near-real-time flag propagation: rather than relying on client SDKs that poll for changes on an interval, FeatBit pushes flag and segment changes to connected SDKs over WebSocket connections, with the company stating that changes made in the UI reach connected SDKs in under 100 milliseconds. This streaming architecture is designed to minimize the latency between a flag change and its effect in production, which matters for use cases like emergency kill switches, where teams need to disable a broken feature immediately rather than waiting for a polling interval to elapse.

FeatBit ships official SDKs for .NET/C#, JavaScript, React, React Native, Node.js, Java, Python, and Go, and it also provides OpenFeature providers, aligning it with the vendor-neutral OpenFeature specification that lets teams swap feature flag backends with reduced code churn. For teams operating at the edge or across multiple regions, FeatBit offers a Relay Proxy, distributed as a 'FeatBit Agent,' which caches flag data closer to application servers and reduces the number of connections back to the core FeatBit services. Deployment options span Docker Compose for local or small-scale self-hosting, Kubernetes via Helm charts maintained in a separate repository, Terraform modules for AWS, and Azure Container Apps, giving infrastructure teams several supported paths to run FeatBit inside their own cloud environment or on-premises. The company also promotes a cloud-hosted SaaS option and a hybrid model, so teams that do not want to operate the platform themselves can still use FeatBit's flag evaluation engine as a managed service, with pricing available on request.

On the pricing side, FeatBit's self-hosted tiers are structured around feature access and support level rather than usage-based metering. The free Foundation tier is the full open-source platform under MIT license, self-hosted with complete data ownership, and includes the core flag management console, REST API, SDKs, webhooks, WebSocket-based real-time updates, basic role-based access control, and community support through Discord and GitHub issues. Above that sits an Enterprise self-hosted tier priced at 3,999 dollars per year, which adds advanced role-based access control as a roughly 600-dollar-per-year add-on, email and priority support, audit logs, flag approval workflows, a high-availability advisor, and support for up to 99 auto-sync agents (Relay Proxy instances) across a deployment. At the top, an Enterprise Premium tier offers custom pricing for large-scale deployments that need 100 or more auto-sync agents, dedicated engineering support, custom SLAs, and formal onboarding and training. A consistent marketing message across FeatBit's own materials is that none of its plans charge based on number of seats, number of monthly active users, or number of API calls, positioning the pricing model as more predictable than typical usage-metered SaaS competitors, and the company claims this structure can cut feature flag and experimentation costs by a large multiple compared to seat- or MAU-priced alternatives for teams operating at scale.

Functionally, beyond basic on/off toggles, FeatBit supports percentage-based progressive rollouts starting as low as one percent of traffic, individual user targeting, reusable audience segments built from user attributes, multivariate flags for A/B and multivariate testing, and built-in experimentation tooling for measuring the impact of a rollout against product metrics. It includes audit logging for compliance and change tracking, scheduled flag changes and flag-change approval workflows for teams that need governance controls before a flag ships to production, and integrations with common observability and alerting tools such as Datadog, New Relic, Grafana, and Slack, along with OpenTelemetry support for tracing. More recently, FeatBit has leaned into an 'AI-native' positioning, publishing an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server, hosted at mcp.featbit.co, that lets AI coding agents such as Claude Code create, evaluate, list, and update feature flags through natural-language instructions rather than manual console interaction. This MCP server is built on .NET 10, ASP.NET Core, and .NET Aspire, and is designed as a thin proxy that forwards a user's own FeatBit API credentials with each request rather than storing them centrally. The company frames this AI tooling around use cases like controlling which versions of AI agent skills or tools are active for different user cohorts, and running progressive rollouts of AI-generated or AI-assisted features with the same safety rails used for traditional feature flags.

FeatBit's target audience skews toward engineering and platform teams at organizations that want infrastructure ownership and data residency control, ranging from smaller engineering teams that cannot justify a large per-seat feature-flag SaaS bill to larger, security-conscious organizations that prefer or are required to self-host third-party tooling. In the competitive landscape, FeatBit is most frequently benchmarked against LaunchDarkly, the dominant commercial feature management platform known for its breadth of enterprise features and experimentation suite but also known for usage-based pricing that scales quickly with MAU and seats. FeatBit is also compared against other open-source feature flag tools, principally Flagsmith, which is built on Python and PostgreSQL and licensed under a BSD 3-Clause variant, and Unleash, which is built on Node.js and PostgreSQL and licensed under Apache 2.0 and is generally regarded as the most established open-source option with the broadest SDK ecosystem. Split.io (now part of Harness) is another named competitor in the broader feature-experimentation space, typically positioned closer to LaunchDarkly as an enterprise-grade, primarily SaaS-first offering. Relative to these peers, FeatBit's core differentiation claims are its MIT-licensed open-core model with no artificial seat, MAU, or API-call limits even on paid tiers, its .NET and MongoDB-based architecture (distinct from the Node/Postgres stacks common among its open-source peers), its sub-100-millisecond WebSocket-based flag propagation, and its more recent push into AI-agent tooling via the MCP server and 'FeatBit Skills' for AI coding assistants. Overall, FeatBit occupies a niche within the feature-flag category as a self-hosting-first, cost-predictable alternative aimed at teams that are willing to operate their own infrastructure in exchange for lower long-run cost and full control over where flag evaluation data lives.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '94397512-e81a-4da3-8e0a-9e8fa8ba4e79';

