-- ── Feathery ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Feathery is a low-code form and workflow builder that lets developers and product teams design pixel-perfect, white-labeled forms with advanced conditional logic, a JavaScript and React SDK, and 100+ integrations.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Feathery Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Feathery review covering pricing, features, integrations, compliance, and top alternatives like Typeform, Jotform, Formstack and Tally for 2026 buyers.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Feathery is a low-code form and workflow-building platform originally built for developers and product teams who need more control than typical form tools provide. At its core, the product lets users design forms and multi-step user journeys through a visual, drag-and-drop editor while retaining developer-grade extensibility: a natural-language Rule Builder for conditional logic, a JavaScript editor for custom scripting, and a React and JavaScript SDK that lets engineers embed forms directly into web and mobile applications with minimal code. This combination of a no-code style editor and code-level override capability is Feathery's central technical differentiator, positioning it between simple consumer form builders and fully custom, hand-coded onboarding flows.

The company was founded in 2021 by Peter Dun, who studied computer science at Stanford and previously worked at Robinhood, together with co-founder Zack Khan, who had prior experience as a product manager at Nextdoor and in marketing at Hightouch. Feathery spent roughly a year working with beta customers in fintech and healthcare before opening the product for public access in July 2022 via a launch post titled 'Announcing Feathery.' The founding thesis was that product teams at most technology companies were hand-coding critical forms, such as signup, onboarding, and payment flows, piece by piece, and that a low-code platform could let those teams retain ownership and speed without sacrificing the polish expected of a modern product surface. The company later raised a Seed round (announced March 2024) and received a MassChallenge grant (announced April 2025) before closing a Series A round announced in July 2026, bringing total funding to 30 million dollars. Investors in the Series A included Portage Ventures, Index Ventures, Allstate Strategic Ventures, Clocktower Ventures, Erie Strategic Ventures, and Bain Capital Ventures.

Technically, Feathery forms are built around a container-based layout system with themeable styles that can be applied consistently across many forms, plus support for partial submissions and persisted user progress so respondents can leave and resume a form later. Logic in Feathery is expressed either through the visual Rule Builder, which lets non-engineers define conditions in natural language, or through custom JavaScript for edge cases and error handling that a purely visual rule system cannot express. Data can be read from external APIs and written back into a company's internal systems as part of a form's submission flow, and the platform supports native A/B testing and analytics for optimizing conversion on live forms, a capability the company positions as differentiated from simpler competitors. Authentication is supported through Firebase and Stytch, identity and fraud checks through providers such as Plaid, Alloy, and LexisNexis, and payments are handled through a native Stripe integration. Feathery advertises more than 100 (and, per newer marketing material, over 150) integrations spanning CRMs such as Salesforce, email and analytics tools, payment processors, and project management systems, alongside SMS one-time-password verification for identity flows.

Pricing is structured in three publicly listed tiers on the official pricing page. The Free plan costs 0 dollars and includes up to 500 monthly submissions, 5 live forms, 10 megabyte file uploads, 1 seat, unlimited questions, pages, conditions, styles and components, partial submissions, standard integrations, Stripe payments, Salesforce, SMS one-time-password, Plaid, Alloy and LexisNexis identity checks, Firebase and Stytch authentication, SOC 2 coverage, and community forum support. The Growth plan is custom-priced and adds unlimited submissions, custom numbers of live forms, removal of Feathery branding, custom SEO metadata, custom HTML and CSS, a custom subdomain, CAPTCHA, native A/B testing, logic and API connectors, a custom DNS domain, premium integrations, HIPAA, GDPR and data sovereignty options, and priority email and live chat support. The Business plan, also custom-priced, layers on role-based access controls, single sign-on, audit logs, a white-label editor, multiple workspaces, a full compliance suite, and priority support plus custom form-building services. Earlier in the company's history, third-party marketplaces and review aggregators cited fixed monthly prices for mid-tier plans (commonly referenced around 49 to 99 dollars per month and around 190 dollars per month for a higher tier), but the current official pricing page presents only a free self-serve tier with the two higher tiers sold on a custom-quote basis, reflecting the company's shift toward larger, higher-touch enterprise accounts.

Feathery's target audience has evolved alongside the product. In its earlier years it was marketed broadly to product and engineering teams at startups and SaaS companies who needed sophisticated, brand-consistent forms for onboarding, signup, and payment collection without hand-coding every flow. More recently, the company has concentrated its go-to-market and product investment on financial services, specifically wealth management (RIAs, broker-dealers, and banks handling client onboarding and account opening), insurance carriers and managing general agents (underwriting, enrollment, claims, and submission intake), and insurance brokers and wholesalers (policy analysis, proposal generation, and agency management system data entry). The company states it has processed more than 10 million workflows and, as of its Series A announcement, serves more than 300 firms across insurance and wealth management, processing tens of millions of monthly submissions for named clients including Sequoia Financial Group, Banner Life, The Baldwin Group, RFG Advisory, LPL, and Hiscox.

Among general-purpose form builders, Feathery is most often compared to Typeform, Jotform, Formstack, and Tally. Feathery's own comparison content frames Typeform and Formstack as offering only basic conditional logic, while Feathery adds a layer of custom JavaScript for handling edge cases, native A/B testing for optimization, and deeper self-hosted, fully brand-controlled forms rather than forms that remain visually tied to the vendor's own hosted experience. Against Tally, which is positioned as an ultra-simple, largely free form builder well suited to small businesses and individual creators, Feathery differentiates on production-grade, pixel-level design control and logic depth aimed at product teams rather than solo users; reviewers note Tally lacks the automation depth and AI tooling needed for complex workflows. Against Jotform, which competes on breadth of templates and out-of-the-box integration coverage for a wide range of use cases, Feathery differentiates on developer embeddability via its React and JavaScript SDK and on identity, authentication and payments integrations aimed at regulated, higher-stakes use cases. G2 lists Feathery with a 4.7 out of 5 rating from a modest base of about a dozen reviews, with users praising ease of use, customizable templates, and responsive customer support, while noting a steeper learning curve for non-technical users and occasional friction integrating with marketing automation platforms compared to more consumer-oriented tools.

On security and compliance, Feathery advertises SOC 2 coverage on its free tier and expands to HIPAA, GDPR, and data sovereignty options, single sign-on, role-based access control, and audit logging on its higher tiers, features aimed squarely at the regulated financial services and healthcare buyers the company increasingly serves. The architecture separates the visual builder and hosted form runtime from a developer-facing SDK layer, allowing the same underlying form definitions to be rendered either through Feathery's own hosted pages or embedded inside a customer's own web or mobile application, with styling and logic that can be set programmatically at runtime.

The most consequential development in Feathery's recent history is its repositioning from a horizontal, developer-first form builder into a vertical, AI-driven 'operating and decisioning' platform purpose-built for financial services. Marketing material from mid-2026 describes the product as encompassing not just forms but document intelligence with claimed 98-plus percent data extraction accuracy, eSignature and template generation, meeting intelligence that extracts structured data from audio and meeting recordings, and a natural-language AI assistant called Robin for building and managing workflows without code. This evolution mirrors a broader trend among form and intake-automation startups moving up the stack into AI-assisted document and workflow automation, and it appears to have coincided with the company's Series A fundraise, which was explicitly earmarked for deepening AI capabilities, expanding a cross-client data network, and hiring across engineering and go-to-market functions. For buyers evaluating Feathery purely as a general-purpose form builder, this strategic focus on financial services is a relevant consideration, since newer product investment and support are increasingly oriented toward insurance and wealth management use cases rather than horizontal SaaS onboarding forms.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'acaa6370-6b47-4ce4-a037-fe2c52fd137b';

