-- ── Featurebase ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Featurebase is a customer feedback and product management platform that combines feedback boards, public roadmaps, changelogs, and an AI-powered support inbox in one workspace, often compared to Canny.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (paid plans from $29/seat/month, billed yearly)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$3 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Tallinn, Estonia$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Featurebase Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Featurebase review: feedback boards, roadmaps, changelogs and AI support in one tool. See pricing plans, key features, pros, cons and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Featurebase is a customer feedback and product management platform built around three connected pillars: a public feedback board where users submit and vote on feature requests, a visual product roadmap that shows what is planned, in progress, and shipped, and a changelog system for announcing releases through a public page, email digests, and in-app widgets. The product is frequently positioned as a modern, better-designed alternative to older feedback tools such as Canny, UserVoice, Productboard, and Frill, and it has more recently expanded into a broader customer support suite that also includes a shared inbox, live chat, and an AI support agent, making it comparable in places to helpdesk products like Intercom and Zendesk as well as pure feedback tools.

Featurebase was founded at the end of 2020 by Robi Rohumaa and Bruno Hiis, with Markus Palm later joining as a co-founder focused on go-to-market, all based in Tallinn, Estonia. The founders started the company after experiencing firsthand how messy and unstructured feedback collection was at a previous startup, and they set out to build, in Bruno Hiis's words, a '10x better solution' than the expensive, stagnant, and poorly designed tools that dominated the category at the time. Featurebase has been built and run as a small, bootstrapped team of around three people, has raised no external venture funding, and describes itself as profitable. Public revenue estimates place the company at roughly 30,000 dollars in annual revenue in 2023, growing to about 54,500 dollars in 2024, figures that reflect its lean, founder-led operating model rather than a venture-scale trajectory. Despite its small team, the company reports serving well over a thousand customers across more than 180 countries, with named users including Lovable, Raycast, and n8n appearing in its marketing and review-site testimonials.

Technically, Featurebase centers on a hosted feedback portal that can be embedded in a product through in-app widgets or accessed as a standalone branded page, often on a custom domain. Customers and internal team members submit ideas, upvote existing posts, and comment on them, while admins organize submissions into boards, apply custom statuses, and merge duplicate requests to keep the backlog clean. An AI layer analyzes incoming feedback to detect near-duplicate submissions automatically, surface patterns across large volumes of requests, and help prioritize which ideas matter most, including a revenue-based prioritization view that links feedback to underlying customer and subscription data so teams can see which requests come from paying or high-value accounts. When a request status changes or a related item ships, everyone who voted or commented is automatically notified, which closes the feedback loop without manual follow-up. The public roadmap surfaces these same items in a kanban- or timeline-style view, and the changelog module lets teams publish release notes with rich media, tag them by category, and push them to users via email, an embeddable widget, or a dedicated changelog page.

On the support side, Featurebase has added a unified inbox that consolidates conversations arriving from in-app chat, email, Slack, and Discord into a single queue, along with an AI support agent the company calls Fibi. Fibi has context across the entire Featurebase workspace, including help center articles, past support conversations, existing feedback posts, changelogs, and the roadmap, which lets it answer customer questions automatically, log new feature requests or bug reports on a customer's behalf by matching them to existing posts or creating new ones, and execute configurable workflows such as extending a trial or applying a discount. A companion help center module offers a Notion-style editor for writing documentation, AI-native search that surfaces instant answers from that documentation, and multi-brand support for teams that run more than one product or customer-facing brand, with claimed support for content in 40 or more languages. Featurebase integrates with a wide set of third-party tools, including Slack, Discord, Intercom, HubSpot, Zendesk, Jira, Linear, GitHub, ClickUp, Azure DevOps, Segment, and Zapier, letting product and support teams sync statuses, create issues from feedback posts, and pipe conversations in from the channels their users already use.

Featurebase's pricing follows a per-seat, tiered subscription model layered on top of a permanent free plan. The Free plan supports a single seat with live chat, unlimited conversations, a unified inbox and ticketing system, a mobile app, and internal notes, making it usable for solo founders or very early-stage products that want to try the feedback and support workflow before paying. The Growth plan is billed at 29 dollars per seat per month on an annual cycle and adds the Fibi AI agent, email support, an AI copilot for support agents, AI-generated replies and macros, custom domains, basic analytics, and access to core integrations, with AI resolutions billed separately at roughly 0.49 dollars each. The Professional plan, at 59 dollars per seat per month annually, is aimed at scaling and multi-team organizations and adds Slack-based support, workflow automation, SLAs, user segmentation, multilingual support, API, MCP, and webhook access, along with a number of free lower-tier 'lite' seats bundled in. The Enterprise plan, at 99 dollars per seat per month annually and gated behind a sales demo, adds a multi-brand workspace, SSO and identity management, custom admin roles, deeper HubSpot integration, Azure DevOps and Active Directory integrations, and custom invoicing. Featurebase also runs a startup program offering a steep discount, reported at around 86 percent off, plus a free year of the Fibi AI agent for companies less than two years old with fewer than six employees, a clear signal of its continued focus on early-stage software teams even as its enterprise tier has grown more sophisticated.

Featurebase's target audience spans early-stage and fast-growing SaaS startups that want an affordable, fast-to-set-up feedback and roadmap tool, through to scaling product and support organizations that need SLAs, workflow automation, and multi-brand support. Product managers use it to centralize and prioritize incoming feature requests with real usage and revenue context, support and success teams use the inbox and Fibi AI agent to resolve routine tickets without expanding headcount, and marketing or go-to-market teams use the public changelog and roadmap as a transparency and retention tool that keeps users informed about what is shipping. Compared with Canny, independent reviews consistently note that Featurebase bundles a support inbox and live chat alongside its feedback toolkit and bills per seat rather than by tracked user, and that its AI-assisted duplicate detection and triage are considered strong, while Canny is generally viewed as having deeper analytics, a more mature enterprise feature set, and a longer integration catalog after operating in the category for longer. Against Productboard and UserVoice, which lean toward heavier, more process-driven product management workflows for larger organizations, Featurebase is typically positioned as the faster-to-adopt, more design-forward option better suited to smaller and mid-market teams. Against Frill, a lighter and cheaper feedback-only tool, Featurebase differentiates through its broader feature set spanning support, help center, and AI automation rather than being a single-purpose voting board. The company operates on EU infrastructure and states SOC 2, GDPR, and CCPA compliance, and reports greater than 99.9 percent uptime with sub-150 millisecond latency, details aimed at reassuring security- and reliability-conscious buyers evaluating it against larger, better-funded competitors. Overall, Featurebase illustrates a common trajectory in the feedback-management category: a narrowly scoped, well-designed voting-and-roadmap tool that has expanded outward into adjacent support and help-center functionality as its founders sought a larger addressable market without taking on outside investment.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '69ed37d5-2093-4b7b-87b5-2affc6a03505';

