-- ── FeedHive ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FeedHive is an AI-powered social media management platform that helps businesses create, schedule, recycle, and analyze content across Instagram, X, LinkedIn, Facebook, TikTok, YouTube, Pinterest, and more from a single workspace.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$19/month (Creator plan, billed monthly; lower with annual billing)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$2-10 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Zurich, Switzerland$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FeedHive Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FeedHive review: AI content creation, evergreen recycling, and multi-platform scheduling. See 2026 pricing tiers, features, pros, cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FeedHive is an AI-powered social media management and automation platform built to help solo creators, brands, and agencies plan, generate, schedule, publish, and analyze content across multiple social networks from a single workspace. The product positions itself around four core promises: AI-assisted content creation, visual and rule-based scheduling, automatic recycling of high-performing evergreen posts, and multi-platform publishing that reformats a single piece of content into channel-specific versions for each connected network. It supports publishing to Facebook, Instagram, X (formerly Twitter), LinkedIn, TikTok, YouTube, Pinterest, Google Business Profile, Threads, and Discord, and connects to automation tools such as Zapier and Make for broader workflow integration.

FeedHive was founded by Simon Hoiberg, who began building the product in 2020 out of Zurich, Switzerland, with a public launch that followed in early 2021. The company has been built and grown as a bootstrapped business without external venture funding, a fact the founder has referenced publicly, including a widely shared account of an early misstep in which he over-hired a team on minimal revenue and had to scale back down, a lesson he later cited as informing FeedHive's lean, founder-led operating approach. As of the most recent information available, the company operates with a small team of roughly 2 to 10 employees and is headquartered in Zurich. Third-party company-data aggregators have estimated FeedHive's annual recurring revenue in the low hundreds of thousands of dollars, consistent with a profitable, tightly run, founder-operated SaaS business rather than a venture-backed scale-up; these figures are third-party estimates and not officially disclosed by the company.

Technically, FeedHive is a cloud-based, browser-accessed SaaS application. Users connect their social accounts through each platform's official API (for example, Meta's Graph API for Facebook and Instagram, and the respective developer APIs for LinkedIn, X, TikTok, YouTube, and Pinterest), after which FeedHive's scheduling engine queues and dispatches posts at configured future times. The scheduling system is built around what the platform calls posting plans and conditions, letting users define recurring publishing cadences, best-time recommendations, and platform-specific formatting rules so that a single draft can be automatically adapted (cropped, captioned, or reformatted) for each destination network rather than requiring the user to manually rebuild the post for every channel. A standout piece of the product is its content recycling engine, which identifies posts that performed well historically and automatically resurfaces or reschedules them as evergreen content, reducing the manual effort of repeatedly promoting durable, high-value posts.

On the AI side, FeedHive offers generative tools for drafting on-brand captions and full posts, an AI hashtag generator, and a performance-prediction feature that estimates how a piece of content is likely to perform before it goes live, helping users iterate on copy prior to publishing. The platform has also introduced AI image generation using third-party image models (including Flux Pro and a model referred to as Nano Banana 2), and a feature branded as a 'Vibe Marketing' agent designed to turn a loose idea or prompt into a finished, ready-to-schedule post. More recently, FeedHive has expanded into agentic and developer-facing territory by advertising integrations with coding-agent tooling such as Claude Code and OpenClaw, positioning itself as a platform that can be orchestrated programmatically as part of broader AI-driven marketing workflows, not solely operated through its own web interface. Usage of AI features (content generation, image generation, and automation runs) is metered through an 'AI credits' allowance and an 'automation runs' allowance that scale with each pricing tier.

Beyond scheduling and generation, FeedHive includes team collaboration functionality aimed at agencies and in-house marketing teams: shared workspaces, content approval flows so that clients or managers can review and approve drafts before they go live, commenting and feedback threads on individual posts, and a unified social inbox that lets teams reply to comments and messages across connected platforms without leaving FeedHive. The platform also provides a content calendar view, a template library for reusable post structures, custom labels for organizing content by campaign or client, and analytics for tracking engagement and post performance over time.

FeedHive's pricing is structured as a four-tier subscription with no permanently free plan, though it offers a 7-day free trial that does not require a credit card. The entry-level Creator plan is aimed at individual creators and solopreneurs and includes four connected social accounts, one workspace, several thousand AI credits per month, a limited number of automation runs, roughly two weeks of advance scheduling, and a capped number of scheduled posts, drafts, and templates. The Brand plan roughly doubles the social account allowance to ten accounts and introduces five workspaces, a larger AI credit and automation allotment, longer advance scheduling windows, and adds approval workflows, AI hashtag generation, and performance prediction, making it the natural tier for small marketing teams or brands managing multiple channels. The Business plan, which FeedHive markets as its most popular tier, scales sharply to around 100 social accounts and 50 workspaces with a substantially larger AI credit pool, and removes the caps on scheduled posts, posting plans, and templates entirely, targeting growing agencies and multi-brand marketing operations. At the top, the Agency plan supports roughly 500 social accounts and 100 workspaces, includes a white-label option and priority support, and is aimed squarely at agencies managing many end-client accounts under one roof. Annual billing is available across tiers at a meaningful discount versus paying monthly, and FeedHive has periodically run promotions such as doubling the included AI credits for new trial users during their first few months.

FeedHive competes most directly with Buffer, Hootsuite, Later, and SocialBee in the social media management category, and its positioning leans on being meaningfully cheaper than Hootsuite (whose plans start much higher) while offering AI content generation and, notably, automated content recycling, a capability that Hootsuite does not offer natively. Compared with Buffer, which maintains a free tier and broad platform support with a large, well-established review base, FeedHive differentiates on deeper AI tooling, approval workflows, and evergreen post recycling, but lacks a free plan and has a smaller review footprint overall. Later and SocialBee both compete on visual content planning and broad platform coverage (including networks like Bluesky and Threads), and reviewers generally frame FeedHive as most attractive to budget-conscious small and mid-sized businesses that specifically want AI generation and automated recycling bundled with scheduling, rather than teams whose primary need is enterprise-grade social listening or the widest possible platform matrix.

User feedback compiled from review platforms such as G2 and Capterra is mixed but instructive. Reviewers consistently praise FeedHive's clean, easy-to-use interface, its approval-workflow system for client and manager sign-off, its unified social inbox, and its content recycling engine, which many single out as the platform's standout differentiator relative to competitors. On the downside, a recurring and fairly serious complaint concerns Instagram publishing reliability: multiple users report that scheduled Instagram posts occasionally fail silently or throw errors that are not clearly actionable, prompting some agencies to build manual verification steps into their workflow to confirm posts actually went live. Other commonly cited drawbacks include AI-generated copy that can feel generic without editing to match a brand's voice, pricing that some users consider high relative to competitors at comparable tiers, the absence of a permanently free plan, and the lack of a native iOS or Android mobile application as of mid-2026; FeedHive instead offers a mobile-optimized browser experience that supports viewing calendars and approving posts but is less practical for drafting content or heavy account management from a phone.

From a product-evolution standpoint, FeedHive has moved from a straightforward scheduling-and-recycling tool toward a broader AI marketing platform, layering on generative image tools, prediction features, and agent-style integrations aimed at developers and AI-first marketing teams, while continuing to serve its core base of solo creators, brands, and agencies who need reliable multi-platform publishing. Its bootstrapped, founder-led trajectory, small team size, and Zurich, Switzerland base distinguish it from many venture-funded competitors in the same category, and its pricing and feature ladder are explicitly built to scale from a single creator managing four accounts up through agencies coordinating hundreds of client profiles under one roof.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '0e6192b5-0793-49cb-96c6-12757f88b772';

